aketopoulou takes up theatrical and cinematic works such as Slave Play and The Night Porter, to chart how trauma and sexuality join forces to surge through the aesthetic domain. Putting the psychoanalytic theory of Jean Laplanche in conversation with queer of color critique, performance studies, and philosophy, Sexuality Beyond Consent proposes that enduring the strange in ourselves, not to master trauma but to rub up against it, can open us up to encounters with opacity. The book concludes by theorizing currents of sadism that, when pursued ethically, can animate unique forms of interpersonal and social care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPsychic trauma. 0aQueer theory. 0aSadism. 0aSex (Psychology). 0aSexxPhilosophy. 0aSexual consent. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Sexuality (see also PSYCHOLOGY / Human Sexuality).2bisacsh  aAging.  aBlackness.  aBoyhood.  aChildhood.  aFeminism.  aGender.  aGirlhood.  aHistoriography.  aHumanism.  aHumanness.  aIntegration.  aLiberalism.  aManhood.  aMinstrelsy.  aNationalism.  aNeoliberalism.  aPlantation.  aProtest.  aSentimentalism.  aSlavery.  aVampires.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075163540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479820276.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479820276423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isb